# CI/CD Pipeline Standards

## Pipeline Architecture

Three GitHub Actions workflows enforce quality at different stages:

- `ci.yml` — runs on every push to `develop`/`main` and all PRs
- `build-release.yml` — runs on `v*` tag push; includes all quality gates before building release artifacts
- `security.yml` — runs weekly and on `requirements*.txt` changes; scans for vulnerabilities

## Quality Gates (must pass before merge)

1. **Lint**: `flake8 src/ tests/` — uses project `.flake8` (extend-ignore for style); separate step enforces no bare `except` (E722).
2. **Format**: `black --check --line-length 120 src/ tests/` — must be formatted
3. **Type check**: `mypy src/ --ignore-missing-imports` — no type errors
4. **Secrets detection**: gitleaks pre-commit hook catches credentials before push

## Test Layers

| Layer | Command | Scope |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Unit | `pytest tests/ --ignore=tests/test_ui.py --ignore=tests/test_integration.py` | Isolated module tests with mocks |
| Integration | `pytest tests/test_integration.py -m integration` | Full pipeline: API data -> extract -> report |
| UI | `pytest tests/test_ui.py` | Flask routes + Playwright browser tests |

## Coverage Requirements

- Minimum **49% line coverage** enforced in CI and build-release via `--cov-fail-under=49` (aligned with pyproject.toml); raise toward 80% as tests expand (see docs/TODO-ROADMAP.md TSE-8–TSE-10).
- Coverage report uploaded as artifact on every CI run (Python 3.12 matrix job).
- New features and bug fixes should include corresponding tests where practical.

## Build Validation

- Cross-platform build smoke tests run on macOS and Windows via PyInstaller
- Build must succeed on both platforms before a release can be created
- Version consistency verified: `src/app.py` APP_VERSION must match all other version locations
- **Release builds:** Every new release (tag `vX.Y.Z`) must produce a new build-release .dmg (and Windows .zip) generated from that release version’s code, via `.github/workflows/build-release.yml`; see `release-packaging-12.mdc`

## Security Scanning

- `pip-audit` and `bandit` run in a single consolidated job to minimize runner minutes
- Scans run weekly (Monday 9:00 UTC) and on `requirements*.txt` changes
- Critical findings create a GitHub issue automatically

## Cost Optimization Strategy

All workflows are tuned to minimize GitHub Actions runner costs:

| Runner | Cost | Usage Policy |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `ubuntu-latest` (Linux) | Baseline | All quality gates, tests, security scans |
| `windows-latest` | 2x Linux | Build jobs only; develop/main and release tags only |
| `macos-latest` | 10x Linux | Build jobs only; develop/main and release tags only |

Key optimizations:

- **Concurrency groups** cancel in-progress CI runs when a new push arrives
- **Branch gating**: build-smoke and ui-tests only run on `develop`/`main` branches and PRs targeting them, not on every feature/fix push
- **Dynamic matrix**: unit-tests run Python 3.12 only on feature branches; full 3.11+3.12 matrix on develop/main
- **Pip caching** on all jobs including macOS/Windows builds to reduce install time on expensive runners
- **Consolidated security scans**: pip-audit + bandit in one job instead of two, eliminating redundant runner startup
- **Never use larger runners or GPU instances** — standard GitHub-hosted runners are sufficient

When adding new CI jobs, always use `ubuntu-latest` unless the job specifically requires macOS or Windows. Gate expensive runners behind branch conditions.

## Pre-Commit Hooks (local enforcement)

Developers should install pre-commit hooks for local quality enforcement:

```bash
pip install pre-commit
pre-commit install
```

This runs black, flake8, mypy, and gitleaks on every commit locally.

## Adding New Tests

- Unit tests: `tests/test_<module>.py` mirroring `src/<module>.py`
- Integration tests: add to `tests/test_integration.py` with `@pytest.mark.integration`
- UI tests: add to `tests/test_ui.py` (requires Playwright)
- Shared fixtures: add to `tests/conftest.py`
- Mock API data: add to `tests/data/mock_api_responses.json`
